## Output structure (MANDATORY)

```markdown
# Research — <title>

## 1. Research questions
- Derived from intake unknowns (U1, U2, ...). Each question references its
  intake unknown id.

## 2. Candidate approaches (≥ 2 required)

### Candidate A: <name>
- Description
- Source/reference (existing code path, prior PR, library, paper, etc.)
- Strengths
- Weaknesses (DO NOT skip; if you can't find any, you didn't look hard enough)

### Candidate B: <name>
- Same structure

(Add C, D as needed)

## 3. Counter-evidence (MANDATORY: actively seek why your favorite candidate fails)

For each candidate, write 1-3 ways it could go wrong in this codebase.
If you have ZERO counter-evidence for the leading candidate, write
"counter-evidence not found after N minutes of investigation" — don't
fabricate, but acknowledge the gap.

## 4. Adoption-fitness ranking

| Candidate | Fits codebase conventions | Cost to adopt | Risk if wrong | Total (1-5) |
|---|---:|---:|---:|---:|

## 5. Recommendation

- Chosen: <candidate name>
- Why this over the others (2-3 sentences)
- Conditions under which the recommendation flips (e.g. "if U3 reveals immer
  middleware, switch to candidate B")

## 6. Carry-forward to plan stage
- Open questions still needing plan-stage decisions (not implementation
  decisions — those are for design/architecture)
```

## Hard limits

- ≤ 2000 words (counted)
- ≥ 2 candidate approaches; if you can only think of 1, that's a strong signal
  the problem is under-specified — flag it as a new Unknown
- Every "approach is good" claim MUST be paired with a "but here's how it
  could fail" sentence
